  "base_commit": "7d3596d5436dad6d38c3305dccd7ad7a2914da49",
  "pr_number": 1131,
  "issue_number": 1130,
  "issue_title": "Job `baseSalary` JSON-LD mis-parses \"$150-190k\"-style ranges: the \"k\" suffix only carries min\u2192max, so `minValue` loses its multiplier (150 instead of 150000)",
  "issue_body": "**Labels:** bug, seo\n**Component:** `@heyclaude/registry` \u2014 job posting structured data (JSON-LD)\n**Affected file:** `packages/registry/src/seo.js` (`parseJobCompensation`, lines 383\u2013441; defect at 416\u2013428)\n\n## Summary\n\n`parseJobCompensation` turns a free-text compensation string (e.g. `\"$150k\u2013$190k\"`) into a Schema.org `MonetaryAmount` with `minValue` / `maxValue` for the JobPosting `baseSalary` JSON-LD (built at `seo.js:288` and emitted at `seo.js:324`).\n\nWhen a salary range writes the `k` (thousands) suffix on **only the upper bound** \u2014 the extremely common `\"$150-190k\"`, `\"$80\u2013120k\"`, `\"\u20ac90-130k\"` form \u2014 the parser applies the `k` multiplier to the **max** but not the **min**, producing a nonsensical range like `minValue: 150, maxValue: 190000`.\n\nThe function clearly *intends* to share a single magnitude suffix across both endpoints \u2014 it already has a `fallbackSuffix` mechanism \u2014 but it only wires the carry in one direction (min's suffix \u2192 max). The reverse and far more common case (max has the suffix, min is bare) is not handled.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nA range where either endpoint carries a `k` suffix means both endpoints are in thousands. `\"$150-190k\"` \u2192 `minValue: 150000, maxValue: 190000`.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\n```js\nconst parseAmount = (amount, fallbackSuffix = \"\") => {\n  const hasK = amount.toLowerCase().endsWith(\"k\");\n  const numericText = hasK ? amount.slice(0, -1) : amount;\n  const numeric = Number(String(numericText).replaceAll(\",\", \"\"));\n  if (!Number.isFinite(numeric)) return null;\n  return Math.round(\n    numeric * (hasK || fallbackSuffix.toLowerCase() === \"k\" ? 1000 : 1),\n  );\n};\n\nconst minSuffix = amounts[0].toLowerCase().endsWith(\"k\") ? \"k\" : \"\";   // \u2190 only looks at the MIN\nconst minValue = parseAmount(amounts[0]);                              // \u2190 no fallback at all\nconst maxValue = parseAmount(amounts[1], minSuffix);                   // \u2190 max inherits MIN's suffix\n```\n\nThe shared suffix is derived solely from `amounts[0]` (the min) and only ever flows to `amounts[1]` (the max). The min itself is parsed with no fallback, so when the suffix lives on the max it is never applied to the min.\n\n### Reproduced\n\n| Input | tokens | minValue | maxValue | correct? |\n|-------|--------|----------|----------|----------|\n| `\"$150k-$190k\"` | `[\"150k\",\"190k\"]` | 150000 | 190000 | \u2705 |\n| `\"$150k-190\"`   | `[\"150k\",\"190\"]`  | 150000 | 190000 | \u2705 (min\u2192max carry) |\n| **`\"$150-190k\"`** | `[\"150\",\"190k\"]` | **150** | 190000 | \u274c |\n| **`\"$80\u2013120k\"`**  | `[\"80\",\"120k\"]`  | **80**  | 120000 | \u274c |\n\n## Impact\n\n`baseSalary` is part of the JobPosting JSON-LD HeyClaude emits for SEO / Google for Jobs. A `MonetaryAmount` of `minValue: 150, maxValue: 190000` is invalid salary data: it advertises a range of roughly \"$150 to $190,000\". Google's structured-data validation flags `minValue > maxValue` inversions and implausible ranges, and the rich result (if shown) misrepresents the listing. The `\"$min-maxk\"` form (suffix only on the upper bound) is one of the most common ways salary ranges are written, so this is frequently hit, not an edge case.\n\nSeverity is SEO/structured-data correctness \u2014 no crash \u2014 but it silently emits wrong machine-readable salary data for a large fraction of job listings.\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create/import a job entry with `compensation: \"$150-190k\"` (or `\"$80\u2013120k\"`).\n2. Build its JSON-LD via the job posting builder (`buildJobPostingJsonLd` \u2192 `parseJobCompensation`).\n3. Inspect `baseSalary.value`.\n\n**Result:** `{ minValue: 150, maxValue: 190000 }`. **Expected:** `{ minValue: 150000, maxValue: 190000 }`.\n\n## Root cause\n\nThe magnitude suffix is treated as a property of the first token rather than of the range. Carrying it only min\u2192max handles `\"$150k-190\"` but not the (more common) `\"$150-190k\"`. The fix is to compute one shared suffix from **either** endpoint and apply it to whichever endpoint lacks an explicit one.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\nMake the shared-suffix detection symmetric:\n\n```js\nconst minHasK = amounts[0].toLowerCase().endsWith(\"k\");\nconst maxHasK = amounts[1].toLowerCase().endsWith(\"k\");\n// A \"k\" on either endpoint sets the magnitude for the whole range.\nconst sharedSuffix = minHasK || maxHasK ? \"k\" : \"\";\nconst minValue = parseAmount(amounts[0], sharedSuffix);\nconst maxValue = parseAmount(amounts[1], sharedSuffix);\n```\n\n`parseAmount` already applies `fallbackSuffix` only when the amount has no explicit `k`, so:\n- `\"$150-190k\"` \u2192 both parse with `sharedSuffix=\"k\"` \u2192 150000 / 190000 \u2705\n- `\"$150k-$190k\"` and `\"$150k-190\"` keep working (still 150000 / 190000)\n- `\"$150-190\"` (no suffix anywhere) \u2192 `sharedSuffix=\"\"` \u2192 150 / 190 unchanged\n\nThis preserves every currently-correct case and only changes the broken suffix-on-max ranges.\n\n## Acceptance criteria / test plan\n\n`seo-jsonld.test.ts` (~line 213) covers only `\"$150K \u2013 $190K\"` and `jobs-api.test.ts` only `\"\u20ac90k\u2013\u20ac130k\"` \u2014 both have the suffix on **both** endpoints, so neither pins the buggy path. Add coverage:\n\n- [ ] `\"$150-190k\"` \u2192 `baseSalary.value` is `{ minValue: 150000, maxValue: 190000 }`.\n- [ ] `\"$80\u2013120k\"` \u2192 `{ minValue: 80000, maxValue: 120000 }`.\n- [ ] Existing both-suffixed cases (`\"$150K \u2013 $190K\"`, `\"\u20ac90k\u2013\u20ac130k\"`) stay unchanged.\n- [ ] A bare range with no suffix (`\"$150-190\"`) stays `{ 150, 190 }`.\n- [ ] `minValue <= maxValue` holds for all parsed ranges.\n\n## Notes for reviewers\n\n- Verified against `main`: tokenization splits `\"$150-190k\"` into `[\"150\",\"190k\"]`; with `minSuffix` taken from `amounts[0]` only, `minValue` is parsed without the multiplier \u2192 150.\n- Distinct from previously filed issues (base64/`atob` decode #1114, Discord `truncate` #1125, `tierFromFlags`); this is purely the job compensation parser feeding JSON-LD.\n- Searched open/closed issues and PRs on `JSONbored/awesome-claude` for compensation/salary/baseSalary/minValue/`k`-suffix \u2014 no existing report.\n",
